    then you probably won't ever need to change it.

@{b}Username Textbox@{ub}

    The login name you need to use to log into the site, or anonymous if Anon
    Login is ticked.

@{b}Anon Login CheckMark@{ub}

    For many FTP sites, you don't need a specialised account to access their
    files because they allow anonymous login. If you don't have an account on
    the FTP site, tick this box to perform an anonymous login. Username will
    contain anonymous and password will contain the default anonymous password
    you specified as a Tool Type. This is usually your E-Mail address.

@{b}Password TextBox@{ub}

    This is the password you need to login into the site. If Anon Login is
    ticked, it will contain your default anonymous password.

@{b}Remote Path Textbox@{ub}

    This should contain the path/location of the file on the remote FTP server.
    Remember, most FTP servers are UNIX systems, so the path should be case
    correct too. For example,  /pub/system is not the same as /PUB/system .

@{b}Filename Textbox@{ub}

    This contains the complete filename of the file you wish to download.
    Remember, most FTP servers are UNIX systems, so the filename should be case
    correct. For example, gofetch.lha is not the same as GoFetch.lha .

@{b}Download Textbox@{ub}

    This contains the path where you want to download the file to.

@{b}File Icon@{ub}

    Pressing this will bring up a file requestor asking where you want to
    download files to. Once a directory has been chosen, the path will
    automatically be entered into the Download Textbox.

@{b}OK Button@{ub}

    Pressing this will make the necessary changes to the selected profile.

@{b}Cancel Button@{ub}

    Pressing this will discard any changes and close the edit window.


@endnode

@node "Trans Win" "Go Fetch! - Transfer Window"

                                @{u}Transfer Window@{uu}

@{b}Transfer Gauge@{ub}

    This displays how much of the file you have received so far in Kilobytes, as
    well as the percentage received.

@{b}Abort Button@{ub} (Shortcut: A)

    Pressing this will abort the current file transfer, Go Fetch! will close the
    connection, then continue onto the next profile.

@{b}Stop Button (On Main Window)@{ub}

    Pressing this will abort the current connection, Go Fetch! will close the
    connection to the server, and NOT continue with any of the other profiles.

@endnode

@node "Arexx" "Go Fetch! - Arexx Commands"

                                 @{u}Arexx Commands@{uu}

For examples of how to use AREXX with Go Fetch!, please see included AREXX
scripts.

AREXX PORT: GOFETCH

These returncodes apply to all Arexx Commands
-4 = Command received wrong number of parameters
-3 = Command received parameter of wrong type
-2 = Out of Memory (except where stated)


@{b}Command:@{ub} addanonprofile
@{b}Parameters:@{ub} SITE/A,PORT/A,REMOTEPATH/A,FILENAME/A,LOCALPATH/A
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub} 0 = Success
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Adds a new profile at the end of the profile queue in Go Fetch!. The profile is
automatically saved. The profile will have the username anonymous and the
password as the configured anonymous password in Go Fetch!.


@{b}Command:@{ub}       addprofile
@{b}Parameters:@{ub}    SITE/A,PORT/A,USERNAME/A,PASSWORD/A,REMOTEPATH/A,FILENAME/A,LOCALAPTH/A
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub}   0 = success
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Adds a new profile at the end of the profile queue in Go Fetch!. The profile is
automatically saved.
@{u}(See: editprofile)@{uu}


@{b}Command:@{ub} addsite
@{b}Parameters:@{ub} SITE/A
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub} 0 = Success
             -1 = Failed, could not open site directory file.
             -2 = Failed, Add or Edit window was open.
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Adds URL to the site directory. This cannot be done whilst the Add or Edit
window is open.


@{b}Command:@{ub}       clearlog
@{b}Parameters:@{ub}    NONE
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub}   0 = success
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Clears the Go Fetch! log listview.


@{b}Command:@{ub}       deleteprofile
@{b}Parameters:@{ub}    PROFILE/N
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub}   0 = success
              -1 = Profile doesn't exist.
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Deletes the profile passed by the profile number. Please note that profiles are
are numbered starting at 0. For example if there are 8 profiles in Go Fetch!
then they are numbered from 0 to 7. Do not pass a negative profile number.
@{u}(See: profiles)@{uu}


@{b}Command:@{ub}       editprofile
@{b}Parameters:@{ub}    PROFILE/N,SITE/A,PORT/A,USERNAME/A,PASSWORD/A,REMOTEPATH/A,FILENAME/A,LOCALAPTH/A
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub}   0 = success
              -1 = Profile doesn't exist.
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Edits the profile with the new specified values. Please note that the
profiles are numbered starting at 0. For example, if there are 8 profiles in
Go Fetch!, they will be numbered from 0 to 7. Under no circumstances should
you pass a negative profile number for editing, this will have unpredictable
effects. The profile is automatically saved and the profile listview is automatically
updated to reflect the changes.
@{u}(See: profiles, addprofile)@{uu}


@{b}Command:@{ub}       getanon
@{b}Parameters:@{ub}    NONE
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub}   0 = success
@{b}ReturnString:@{ub}  Default Anonymous Password
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Returns the default anonymous password as a string, which is set in the program
tool types, if the user has not set a password then it will return
nobody@nobody.com


@{b}Command:@{ub}       getdownloadpath
@{b}Parameters:@{ub}    NONE
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub}   0 = success
@{b}ReturnString:@{ub}  Default Download Directory
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Returns the default download directory as a string, which is set in the program
tool types, if the user has not set a default download directory then it will
return ram:


@{b}Command:@{ub} gofetch
@{b}Parameters:@{ub} NONE
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub} 0 = Success
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Simulates the GO button. Go Fetch! will start downloading files and working
through the profiles.


@{b}Command:@{ub}       iconify
@{b}Parameters:@{ub}    NONE
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub}   0 = success
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Iconifies Go Fetch!
@{u}(See: uniconify, iconifystatus)@{uu}


@{b}Command:@{ub}       iconifystatus
@{b}Parameres:@{ub}     NONE
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub}   0 = uniconified
               1 = iconified
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Returns whether Go Fetch is iconified.
@{u}(See: iconify, uniconify)@{uu}


@{b}Command:@{ub}       lockgui
@{b}Parameters:@{ub} NONE
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub} 0 = success
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Locks the Go Fetch! main window from receiving user input. This command is nested,
therefore if you tell the window to lock twice, you must also tell it to unlock
twice. USE WITH CAUTION.
@{u}(See: unlockgui)@{uu}


@{b}Command:@{ub} openaddwindow
@{b}Parameters:@{ub} NONE
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub} 0 = success
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Opens the profile add window, simulates the user pressing the ADD button.


@{b}Command:@{ub} openeditwindow
@{b}Parameters:@{ub} NONE
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub} 0 = success
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Opens the edit window, simulates the user pressing the EDIT button. Please note
that the edit window will not open if a profile isn't active. This command will
return 0 regardless of whether the edit window opened or not.
@{u}(See: setactiveprofile, profiles)@{uu}


@{b}Command:@{ub} profiles
@{b}Parameters:@{ub} NONE
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub} Number of Profiles
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Returns the number of profiles in Go Fetch!. For example, if there are 8
profiles in Go Fetch!, then this command will return 8.


@{b}Command:@{ub} quitgofetch
@{b}Parameters:@{ub} NONE
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub} 0 = success
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Quits Go Fetch!


@{b}Command:@{ub} release
@{b}Parameters:@{ub} NONE
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub} Release Number
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Returns the release number of Go Fetch!. Each public release of Go Fetch! will
have it's release number incremented by 1, independant of the program version.


@{b}Command:@{ub} reloadprofiles
@{b}Parameters:@{ub} NONE
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub} 0 = success
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Forces Go Fetch! to reload the profiles from the profiles file. This has no
real practical use because Go Fetch! automatically updates the profiles
whenever an addition or edit is made. This command may be useful to those who
feel confident enough to edit the profiles file directly, however this is highly
unadvised as an invalid profiles file may have unpredictable effects in Go
Fetch!


@{b}Command:@{ub} savelog
@{b}Parameters:@{ub} PATH/A
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub} 0 = success
            -1 = Unable to save logfile. Check your path.
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Saves the Go Fetch! log with a filename of gofetch.log at the chosen path.


@{b}Command:@{ub} setactiveprofile
@{b}Parameters:@{ub} PROFILE/N
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub} 0 = success
            -1 = Profile doesn't exist
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Highlights the profile entry in the profile listview passed by the profile
number. Please note that profiles are numbered starting at 0. For example if
there are 8 profiles in Go Fetch! then they are numbered from 0 to 7. Do not
pass a negative profile number.
@{u}(See: profiles)@{uu}


@{b}Command:@{ub} stop
@{b}Parameters:@{ub} NONE
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub} 0 = success
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Aborts the current file transfer, and stop Go Fetch! from moving onto the next
profile.


@{b}Command:@{ub} uninconify
@{b}Parameters:@{ub} NONE
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub} 0 = success
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Uniconifies Go Fetch!
@{u}(See: iconify)@{uu}


@{b}Command:@{ub} unlockgui
@{b}Parameters:@{ub} NONE
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub} 0 = success
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Unlocks the Go Fetch! main window to allow user input after the lockgui command
has been issued. This command is nested, therefore if you tell the window to
lock twice, you must also tell it to unlock twice.
@{u}(See: lockgui)@{uu}


@{b}Command:@{ub} windowopen
@{b}Parameters:@{ub} NONE
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub} 0 = No Windows Open
             1 = Add Window Open
             2 = Edit Window Open
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Returns whether any windows are currently open (Add, Edit).



                          @{b}Standard MUI Arexx Commands@{ub}

@{b}Command:@{ub} HELP
@{b}Parameters:@{ub} FILE/A
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub} 0 = success
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Lists GO Fetch Arexx Commands into the file specified.


@{b}Command:@{ub} HIDE
@{b}Parameters:@{ub} NONE
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub} 0 = success
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Iconifies Go Fetch!


@{b}Command:@{ub} INFO
@{b}Parameters:@{ub} ITEM/A
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub} 0 = success
Returns requested string in result.
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Where ITEM is:
TITLE = Title of Application
AUTHOR = Author of Application
COPYRIGHT = Copyright Message
DESCRIPTION = Description of Go Fetch
VERSION = Current Version
BASE = Name of AREXX Port
SCREEN = Name of public screen


@{b}Command:@{ub} QUIT
@{b}Parameters:@{ub} NONE
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub} 0 = success
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Quits Go Fetch!


@{b}Command:@{ub} SHOW
@{b}Parameters:@{ub} NONE
@{b}ReturnCodes:@{ub} 0 = success
@{b}Description:@{ub}
Uniconfies Go Fetch!

@endnode

@node "Scripts" "Arexx Scripts"

                                 @{u}Arexx Scripts@{uu}

These scripts are designed to integrate Go Fetch with other applications, for
example Aweb-II which allows you to automatically create profiles. Scripts for
the other browsers such as Voyager and IBrowse as soon as they have decent AREXX
ports.

If you have any AREXX scripts which integrate Go Fetch! into other software,
please feel free to E-Mail me them and you'll receive a FREE keyfile for future
versions of Go Fetch!

Please note that any submitted AREXX scripts will be distributed with future
versions of Go Fetch!. Upon submitting the author gives their permission for Ian
Chapman and Zeus Developments to distribute and modify the code. Any
modifcations would be commented as so in the source. The original author will
have full credits in the source.

                                 @{b}The Script(s)@{ub}

                                 @{" browser.rexx       " Link "browser.rexx"  }
                                 @{" StartGoFetch.miami " Link "startgofetch.miami"      }
                                 @{" StopGoFetch.miami  " Link "startgofetch.miami"      }
                                 @{" AmFTPtoGoFetch.rexx" Link "amftptogofetch.rexx"     }


@endnode
@node browser.rexx "browser.rexx"
                                 @{b}browser.rexx@{ub}

Notes:
This script has only been tested on Aweb-II version 3.0 and therefore I cannot
guarantee it's compatibility with different versions. The installation procedure
may differ depending on your version of Aweb.

There are two ways in which you can use the script within Aweb. For maximum
flexibility you probably want to use both.

@{b}Use: Method 1@{ub}
@{b}Installation in Aweb (via the AREXX Menu)@{ub}.

Method 1 uses the AREXX script in the AREXX menu of Aweb. This allows you to
mark text (as if you were doing a copy & paste) and selecting the AREXX script
from the menu, it will automatically create a new profile.

1. Open Settings Menu
2. Choose GUI Settings
3. Select the AREXX tab.
4. Press ADD and fill in the following fields.
    Title = Send to Go Fetch!
    Macro = <path to browser.rexx> AWEBSEL

@{b}Use: Method 2@{ub}
@{b}Installation in Aweb (via PopUp Menus)@{ub}

Method 2 uses the AREXX script in a popup menu. This allows you to press the
right mouse button over a link and send the link to Go Fetch! and a profile will
be created for you.

1. Open Settings Menu
2. Choose GUI Settings
4. Select PopUp TAB
3. Press ADD and fill in the following fields
        Type = Link Popup Menu
        Title = Send to Go Fetch!
        Command = RUN <path to browser.rexx> %u

@{b}Use from the command line@{ub}

rx browser.rexx URL <url> TO <download path> PATH <GoFetch Exe>

Where:
@{b}URL@{ub}     is the site you want to create a profile for
@{b}TO@{ub}      (optional) An Alternative download directory, otherwise the default is used.
@{b}PATH@{ub}    (optional) The location of the GoFetch! executable if you want to automatically
        start Go Fetch! and Go.

Examples:

rx browser.rexx URL ftp://site.com/dir/anotherdir/file.lha
rx browser.rexx URL ftp://me:secret@site.com/yetanotherdir/kewl.txt
rx browser.rexx URL ftp.hello.com/pub/gofetch.lha TO work:
rx browser.rexx URL ftp://login:password@ftp.asite.com:2034/pub/file.lha TO work: PATH Work:comms/GoFetch!/GoFetch!


If Go Fetch! is not running then it will attempt to execute it, providing you
have specified its location on the command line. The script will then remember
the Go Fetch! location.

@{b}Return Codes@{ub}
Browser.rexx returns the following values.

0 = Success
1 = Go Fetch! is not running and could not be started
2 = Go Fetch! is not running and couldn't be located.
3 = Go Fetch! is not running and the user chose not to start it.
4 = Unsupported Protocol (Eg trying to use HTTP/FILE/GOPHER etc)
5 = Invalid URL

-ve = Add Profile return value
-4 = Wrong number of parameters passed to Go Fetch!
-3 = Parameter of wrong type passed to Go Fetch!

@endnode
@node startgofetch.miami "startgofetch.miami"

                  @{b}StartGoFetch.miami@{ub} & @{b}StopGoFetch.miami@{ub}

These scripts are designed to automatically start and stop GO Fetch! when you go
online. If the AREXX script finds profiles contained within Go Fetch! it will
tell Go Fetch! to GO, otherwise it will Quit Go Fetch!. When you go offline, the
AREXX scripts tells Go Fetch! to Stop and Quit.

@{b}Miami Deluxe (DX) Installation@{ub}
1. Choose Interfaces.
2. Highlight the interface you want to use Go Fetch! with when you go online.
3. Press Edit
4. Press Events
5. Change "Active Offline" to the location of the StopGoFetch.miami script
6. Change the script type to AREXX
7. Repeat this for "Passive Offline"
8. Change "Online" to the location of the StartGoFetch.miami script, followed by
   the location of your Go Fetch! executable.
9. Change the script type to AREXX
10. Press OK and Save your settings.

@{b}Miami Installation@{ub}

1. Choose Events
2. Change "Active Offline" to the location of the StopGoFetch.miami script
3. Change the script type to AREXX
4. Repeat this for "Passive Offline"
5. Change "Online" to the location of the StartGoFetch.miami script, followed by
   the location of your Go Fetch! executanle
6. Change the script type to AREXX
7. Save your settings.

@endnode

@node amftptogofetch.rexx "amftptogofetch.rexx"

                              @{b}AmFTPtoGoFetch.rexx@{ub}

                                  by Mike King

This script allows you to convert a Batch File from AmFTP into a set of profiles
in Go Fetch!. Please see the AREXX script for information on its use.

@endnode


@node "Tool Types" "Tool Types"

                                   @{u}Tool Types@{uu}

@{b}ANONPASS@{ub}

    This specifies the default password you want to use for anonymous logins.
    This should usually be your E-Mail address. If no password is specified
    then nobody@nobody.com will be used.

@{b}DOWNLOAD@{ub}

    This specifies the default download directory you want to use. If no
    directory is specified then Ram: will be used as the default. Please note
    that if the directory path ends with a directory rather than a device name
    you must add the trailing slash. For example:

    Work:download/     (Valid Path)
    Work:              (Valid Path)
    Work:download      (Invalid Path)

@{b}BEEP@{ub}

    If this tooltype is present then GoFetch! will beep (or play system sample
    etc) when Go Fetch! has finished transferring all profiles.

@endnode

@node "Bug Reports" "Bug Reports"

                                  @{u}Bug Reports@{uu}

The current version of Go Fetch! is still in a beta state which means despite
extensive testing, there may still be bugs. If you discover a bug, please E-Mail
a bug report containing as much information as you can. Try to include the
following.

Machine Description
(Including Model, Processor, RAM, Cards, etc)

AmigaOS Version

TCP/IP Stack you are using
(Including version)

Any Enforcer/Cyberguard/Segtracker/Mungwall output

A good clear desciption of the bug.

If possible, a log file created from Go Fetch!

Details on the FTP site you were using, and the file you were tring to download.

Send bug reports to ian.chapman@bleach.demon.co.uk

@endnode

@node "History" "Program History"

                                    @{u}History@{uu}

Thanks to all those who have registered and sent it suggestions & Bug Fixes.

@{b}Version 0.9b@{ub}

    First Public Beta Release

@{b}Version 0.95b@{ub}

    Second Public Beta Release
    @{b}Bug Fixes:@{ub}
        -Now Snapshots Transfer Window. @{i}(Jostein Klemmetsrud)@{ui}
        -Now Snapshots Add Window
        -Now Snapshots Edit Window
        -Anon Checkmark is now set if profile is anonymous
        -Changed timeout to 25 seconds (was 40)
        -Fixed continuous downloading. Previously it would not continue onto the
        next profile if the main window was not selected. This was due to a quirk
        in MUI. 
        -Moved location of profiles file to the program directory. This might
        resolve conflicts with HappyENV. @{i}(Andreas Boerner)@{ui}
        -Fixed RC 421 Problem. Previously if Go Fetch! received a code 421 on
        login, it would send QUIT then get stuck in a Busy Loop.
        @{i}(Jostein Klemmetsrud)@{ui}
        -Various code optimisations
    @{b}New Features:@{ub}
        -Adds comments to downloaded files. @{i}(Thrasyvoulos Theologou)@{ui}
        -Added Site Directory
    @{b}New Arexx Commands@{ub}
        addanonprofile @{i}(Stephen Bridges)@{ui}
        addsite
        gofetch @{i}(Duane McDonnell, Stephen Bridges)@{ui}
        stop
        windowopen
    @{b}New ARexx Scripts@{ub}
        StartGF.miami
        StopGF.miami
        AmFTPtoGoFetch.rexx
        browser.rexx - UPDATED


@endnode

@node "Future" "Future"

                                     @{u}Future@{uu}

I would like to add the following features to future versions of Go Fetch! If
you have any additional suggestions, then please feel free to E-Mail me.

- Support for HTTP downloads
- Resume for HTTP sites that support it.
- Multiple Simultaneous Downloading
    (Downloading from several sites at the same time)
- CPS Counter
- Bandwidth Setting
    (Set a maximum bandwidth Go Fetch! should use)
- Locale Support
- Alternative profiles files, chosen on command line
- Toggle which displays the full log, or minimum info log.
- Keep connection alive if the next file is on the same server

@endnode

